4326→緯度経度の座標系

london_geo = st_set_crs(london, 4326)
st_is_longlat(london_geo)
## [1] TRUE
london_buff_no_crs = st_buffer(london, dist = 1) #座標系がしっかりしていないと言われる
london_buff = st_buffer(london_geo, dist = 1)
## Warning in st_buffer.sfc(st_geometry(x), dist, nQuadSegs, endCapStyle =
## endCapStyle, : st_buffer does not correctly buffer longitude/latitude data
## dist is assumed to be in decimal degrees (arc_degrees).
london_proj = data.frame(x = 530000, y = 180000) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = 1:2, crs = 27700)
st_crs(london_proj)
#> Coordinate Reference System:
#>   EPSG: 27700 
#>   proj4string: "+proj=tmerc +lat_0=49 +lon_0=-2 ... +units=m +no_defs"

直交座標系において緯度経度1度あたり111320m(約111km)くらいにおいてバッファを書いて変形させる． 直交座標系(27700)では円が正円になるが，緯度経度の地理座標系(4326)では楕円形になっている． よって，距離計算の際には直交座標系を使うのが望ましい．

london_proj_buff = st_buffer(london_proj, 111320)

Buffers around London with a geographic (left) and projected (right) CRS. The gray outline represents the UK coastline.

座標系が違うため，距離計算ができないことの例

st_distance(london_geo, london_proj)
# > Error: st_crs(x) == st_crs(y) is not TRUE

##どの座標系を用いるか GPSなどを用いるようなデータの時は4326を使うのが適当であると言えるし，距離計算などをする際には直交座標系を用いるのが良いと言える．ケースバイケース． epsgを用いると，座標系のコードを調べることができるため，活用すると良い．

lonlat2UTM = function(lonlat) {
  utm = (floor((lonlat[1] + 180) / 6) %% 60) + 1
  if(lonlat[2] > 0) {
    utm + 32600
  } else{
    utm + 32700
  }
}

epsgのコードを出す．

epsg_utm_auk = lonlat2UTM(c(174.7, -36.9))
epsg_utm_lnd = lonlat2UTM(st_coordinates(london))
st_crs(epsg_utm_auk)$proj4string
## [1] "+proj=utm +zone=60 +south +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs"
st_crs(epsg_utm_lnd)$proj4string
## [1] "+proj=utm +zone=30 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs"

library(sf)
library(raster)
library(dplyr)
library(spData)
library(spDataLarge)
library(tmap)    # for static and interactive maps
library(leaflet) # for interactive maps
library(ggplot2) # tidyverse data visualization package
# Add fill layer to nz shape
tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_fill() 
# Add border layer to nz shape
tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_borders() 
# Add fill and border layers to nz shape
tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_fill() +
  tm_borders() 
map_nz = tm_shape(nz) + tm_polygons()
class(map_nz)
## [1] "tmap"
map_nz1 = map_nz +
  tm_shape(nz_elev) + tm_raster(alpha = 0.7)
nz_water = st_union(nz) %>% st_buffer(22200) %>% 
  st_cast(to = "LINESTRING")
map_nz2 = map_nz1 +
  tm_shape(nz_water) + tm_lines()
map_nz3 = map_nz2 +
  tm_shape(nz_height) + tm_dots()
tmap_arrange(map_nz1, map_nz2, map_nz3)

Maps with additional layers added to the final map of Figure 8.1. 

ma1 = tm_shape(nz) + tm_fill(col = "red")
ma2 = tm_shape(nz) + tm_fill(col = "red", alpha = 0.3)
ma3 = tm_shape(nz) + tm_borders(col = "blue")
ma4 = tm_shape(nz) + tm_borders(lwd = 3)
ma5 = tm_shape(nz) + tm_borders(lty = 2)
ma6 = tm_shape(nz) + tm_fill(col = "red", alpha = 0.3) +
  tm_borders(col = "blue", lwd = 3, lty = 2)
tmap_arrange(ma1, ma2, ma3, ma4, ma5, ma6)

The impact of changing commonly used fill and border aesthetics to fixed values. 

tm_shape(nz) + tm_fill(col = "Land_area")
legend_title = expression("Area (km"^2*")")
map_nza = tm_shape(nz) +
  tm_fill(col = "Land_area", title = legend_title) + tm_borders()
tm_shape(nz) + tm_polygons(col = "Median_income")
breaks = c(0, 30000, 40000, 50000)
